{"title":"Evaluating Object Hallucination in Large Vision-Language Models","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"The severity and characteristics of object hallucination in large vision-language models (LVLMs) are unclear, and existing caption-based metrics like CHAIR may be unreliable for LVLM evaluation.","method":"The paper conducts a systematic empirical study on five LVLMs (e.g., LLaVA, MiniGPT-4, InstructBLIP) using MSCOCO and the CHAIR I/S metrics under two captioning prompts. It finds LVLMs often hallucinate more than smaller VLPMs (e.g., LLaVA CHAIR S 32.7 vs OSCAR base 13.0), and that CHAIR is sensitive to instruction phrasing and caption length, leading to instability and parsing challenges for LVLM-style generations. This motivates the need for a more stable and fair evaluation approach tailored to LVLMs."},{"problem":"The underlying drivers of LVLM object hallucination—particularly the role of instruction data distributions—are not well understood.","method":"The authors hypothesize that LVLMs tend to hallucinate (1) objects that frequently appear in instruction data and (2) objects that frequently co-occur with ground-truth objects. They verify this via qualitative analyses (hallucination counts vs. object frequency/co-occurrence) and introduce top-k hit ratios HR_A and HR_C to quantify correlations, showing substantial overlap (e.g., HR_A@10≈0.46–0.55; HR_C@10≈0.56–0.66, increasing with k). These results indicate LVLMs disproportionately hallucinate frequent and co-occurring objects, informing targeted evaluation sampling strategies."},{"problem":"Evaluating LVLM object hallucination needs to be stable across prompts, fair, and scalable to datasets without human annotations, while avoiding brittle caption parsing.","method":"They propose POPE (Polling-based Object Probing Evaluation), which reframes hallucination assessment as binary Yes/No questions about object presence (e.g., “Is there a <object> in the image?”) with a 1:1 balance of ground-truth and nonexistent objects. POPE introduces three negative sampling regimes—Random, Popular (top frequent objects), and Adversarial (top co-occurring with present objects)—to control difficulty. It scales to unannotated datasets by extracting objects via automatic segmentation (SEEM). Experiments show POPE yields consistent model rankings, reveals strong Yes-bias/overconfidence in several LVLMs (~95–100% Yes), has low variance across prompt phrasings, and maintains trends when applied to A-OKVQA/GQA using SEEM."}]}
